#### I investigate aspects of experience that matter in cognitive development, especially related to learning to read (and learning from reading). My interests learning relate back to my experiences as an elementary school teacher, which was my profession prior to starting work in psychology.
  
  
### Publications
Seidenberg, M. S., Borkenhagen, M. C., & Kearns, D. M. (in press). Lost in translation? Challenges in connecting reading science and educational practice. _Reading Research Quarterly_. [`[pdf]`](https://psyarxiv.com/sq4fr/)

Seidenberg, M. S., & Borkenhagen, M. C. (2020). Reading science and educational practice: Some tenets for teachers. _The Reading League Journal, 1_(1), 7-11. [`[pdf]`](./data/seidenberg_etal_2020_rlj.pdf)

Cox, C., Borkenhagen, M. C., & Seidenberg, M. S. (2019) Efficiency of learning in experience-limited domains: Generalization beyond the WUG test. In A.K. Goel, C.M Seifert, & C. Freksa (Eds.), _Proceedings of the 41st Annual Conference of the Cognitive Science Society_ (pp. 1566-1571). Montreal, QB. Cognitive Science Society. [`[pdf]`](https://cogsci.mindmodeling.org/2019/papers/0281/0281.pdf)

### Under review
Lewis, M., Borkenhagen, M. C., Converse, E., Lupyan, G., & Seidenberg, M. S. (2020, March 30). What might books be teaching young children about gender?. [doi: 10.31234/osf.io/ntgfe](https://psyarxiv.com/ntgfe/)

Sen, A., Cox, C. R., Borkenhagen, M. C., Seidenberg, M. S., & Zhu, J. (2020, July 2). Learning to read through machine teaching. [doi: 2006.16470v2](https://arxiv.org/pdf/2006.16470.pdf)
